snippet.textDisplay: Not a bad movie. All the subversion in The Last Jedi kinda wrote the finale into a corner. Too many questions to come back to and answer. Who were Rei's parents? Why is there a force connection between Ben and Rei? Who's the villain? What are Kylo's motivations? Why is princess Leia a force user/jedi master training Rei all of a sudden? What happened to the resistance which was basically destroyed in entirety in The Last Jedi? Why did some storm troopers like Finn revolt in the first place? The movie faithfully, albeit quickly, gives the answers to most of these questions, some of which had no right being questions in a three part story. I actually really enjoyed the Sith artifact plot device, too bad the dagger wasn't seen in episodes 7 or 8. Little connecting pieces like that could have made The Rise of Skywalker transcendent. But hindsight is next year.
snippet.textOriginal: Not a bad movie. All the subversion in The Last Jedi kinda wrote the finale into a corner. Too many questions to come back to and answer. Who were Rei's parents? Why is there a force connection between Ben and Rei? Who's the villain? What are Kylo's motivations? Why is princess Leia a force user/jedi master training Rei all of a sudden? What happened to the resistance which was basically destroyed in entirety in The Last Jedi? Why did some storm troopers like Finn revolt in the first place? The movie faithfully, albeit quickly, gives the answers to most of these questions, some of which had no right being questions in a three part story. I actually really enjoyed the Sith artifact plot device, too bad the dagger wasn't seen in episodes 7 or 8. Little connecting pieces like that could have made The Rise of Skywalker transcendent. But hindsight is next year.
